description: From Latin ablūdō (“differ from”), from ab (“from”) + lūdō (“play; trick”).

verbs.description: ablude (third-person singular simple present abludes, present participle abluding, simple past and past participle abluded)

entries.meaning: (obsolete, intransitive) To be unlike; to differ.
examples: Neither doth it much ablude from this, that our English divines at Dort call the decree of God, whereby he hath appointed in and by Christ to save those that repent, believe, and persevere, decretum annunciatum salutis omnibus, etc.
